section.para:
    &framework-name; provides an interface called com.xaf.page.ServletPage
    and an implementing class called com.xaf.page.AbstractServletPage
    to create web pages purely in Java. The AbstractServletPage class should be 
    extended since it does not define any behavior (the methods are empty).         
    For example, &explorer-name; 
    uses a class called com.xaf.ace.AceServletPage which overwrites
    the methods defined in AbstractServletPage such as handlePageHeader
    and handlePageMetaData. It also defines other methods such as 
    transform which can be used by other subclasses.

    Developers should create classes extending com.xaf.page.AbstractServletPage
    and then overwrite the various methods to define the  functionality of each page. 
    The following is an example of the dialogs listing page in &explorer-name;:

         com.xaf.ace.AppDialogsPage  class




public class AppDialogsPage extends AceServletPage
{
    ...

    public void handlePageBody(PageContext pc) throws ServletException, IOException
    {
        ServletContext context = pc.getServletContext();
        DialogManager manager = DialogManagerFactory.getManager(context);
        manager.addMetaInfoOptions();

        String testItem = getTestCommandItem(pc);
        if(testItem != null)
        {
            ...
        }
        else
        {
            ...
        }
    }
}



        The example above describes how a web page can be created by overwriting the various methods 
        available in com.xaf.ace.AceServletPage which extends the 
        com.xaf.page.AbstractServletPage.  The com.xaf.ace.AceServletPage
        defines the functionality common to all pages in &explorer-name; and the AppDialogsPage base 
        class extending this class can define content specific to the page itself.
